metadata.name: Dragon Rave #112
metadata.description:
Welcome to the Dragon Rave!

It is where all the cool dragons hang out, as well as the hot ones!

There are many variations of dragons in this rave:
- Disco Dragons are colourful and like to play
- Crystal Dragons are chill and laid-back
- Dark Energy Dragons are moody and twitchy, especially the spiky ones
- Some dragons are skinny, some are curly and like to cuddle

Note: You need to click on the display to get the dancing and music started!

Of course, there is a pumping trance track playing over the PA, so turn the sound on!
If you don't like the sound, press "m" to mute. (sound is coded using Tone.js synths - no samples)

Press "p" to pause the gyrations if you want to take a photo (press "s" to capture a picture)

Eventually (after 30 minutes or so), the sound will get more and more glitchy and end up in a noisy mess. Time to go home or bar-hopping...

metadata.name: z-pattern : stacked noise #3
metadata.description:
This work is an exploration of pattern interferences that can happen in depth perception.

Each token is composed of 35 frames stacked in the z-axis. Each frame is a simple noise field with several detail levels displayed on transparent background.

The 3D stack is oriented at random for each token.

This work is interactive : you can press and drag your mouse around the canvas to explore different views and see several patterns.

metadata.description:

metadata.name: CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE #131
metadata.description:
1 of 5 in CENTURY-XXX, Series 2
Edition of 1000

Tribute to Herbert W. Franke
“In Honor of the Dinosaur of Computer Art” 

Herbert W. Franke, a pioneer of computer art, passed away on July 16, 2022 at the age of 95. CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE is an homage to Franke’s MONDRIAN software developed for the Texas Instruments TI 99/4 home computer in 1979, and it’s a fundraiser to digitize his archive:

“Our goal is to raise 20,000 Euro so that ZKM Karlsruhe can digitize Herbert W. Franke’s 1,800 manuscripts and make them publicly available. If we raise more money, it will be donated to the Rütgers Foundation which supports children and young adults in Africa so that they can get access to and work with technology.” 

Each frame, a single “pixel” is added to the CENTURY-XXX-METAFRANKE image. When the software first loads, 100,000 frames are run in the background to start things off. Keep it running for hours or days to see it transform entirely — it’s an “infinite animation.”
